        jTextArea7.setText("Huge Geographic Differences\n________________________________________\nColin Brechbill - Thursday, August 01, 2013\nHuge Geographic Differences The US housing market can no longer be painted with one brush, as the housing recovery is playing out very differently across the country. Here are some anecdotes gleaned: Florida on sale to the world. Investors, investors, and investors. From Russia to China to the UK to Brazil, Florida is attracting investors from all over the world. Domestically, the institutional single-family renters are competing with local flippers, too. Good fini ..\n\nComments (0) | Trackbacks (0) | Permalink \n  \nWall Street Wants Rental Houses\n________________________________________\nColin M. Brechbill - Thursday, September 06, 2012\nThe time to get into cash flow properties is NOW. Read this article! http://finance.fortune.cnn.com/2012/07/24/wall-street-foreclosures/ If big Wall Street hedge funds are trying to figure out how buy massive amounts of single family houses. The hard part, which they will soon figure out, is property management. The reason that they want to get in on these foreclosure properties is simple; The returns can't be beat. If and when these hedge funds figure out how to acquire an ..\n\nComments (0) | Trackbacks (0) | Permalink \n  \nBuffett Bets Big On US Houseing Market\n________________________________________\nColin Brechbill - Thursday, June 21, 2012\n*Buffett bets big on US housing market Warren Buffett, arguably the world’s most famous investor, is looking to take a $3.85 billion bet on a US housing market recovery. His firm Berkshire Hathaway Inc has submitted a $3.85 billion bid for the mortgage and loan business of bankrupt Residential Capital LLC. Buffett is taking a “picks and shovels” approach to his investment in a US housing recovery by buying firms he believes will benefit strongly ..\n\nComments ((Disabled)) | Trackbacks (0) | Permalink \n  \nThe Real Estate Cycle: Where Are We Now?\n________________________________________\nColin Brechbill - Thursday, June 07, 2012\nReal estate prices, as with most financial markets, tend to follow a pattern. For the purpose of this article, we'll call this pattern \"The Real Estate Cycle.\" There are many theories out there about The Real Estate Cycle, but the one I like best is called \"The Great 18-Year Real Estate Cycle.\" Back in the 30's a real estate economist named Homer Hoyt discovered that real estate prices seemed to ebb and flow on an almost perfect 18 year schedule. Hoyt's theory was later used and refined by n ..\n\nComments ((Disabled)) | Trackbacks (0) | Permalink \n  \nAustralian investors eye American property\n________________________________________\nColin Brechbill - Wednesday, April 18, 2012\nInvestors are looking to America, where property is at rock-bottom prices after the sub-prime mortgage meltdown, but analysts warn the recovery is a long way away. Transcript: TICKY FULLERTON, PRESENTER: America's subprime mortgage meltdown is still recent history but that's not stopping investors from buying property in the United States at rock-bottom prices. Despite the continuing fallout from the global  ..\n\nComments (1) | Trackbacks (0) | Permalink \n  \nSouthwest Florida apartments fullest in state\n________________________________________\nColin Brechbill - Wednesday, April 11, 2012\nForeclosure crisis leads to surplus of renters in the Fort Myers-Naples area, a trend unlikely to slow anytime soon. At 94.2 percent, the occupancy rate for apartments/condo conversions in the Fort Myers/Naples area is the highest in the state, according to a report by ALN Apartment Data. Carrollton, Texas-based ALN, which tracks apartment/condo conversions complex data in six Southern states, said Fort Myers-Naples occupancy rose from 91.9 percent from February 2011 to February 2 ..\n\nComments (1) | Trackbacks (0) | Permalink \n  \nAn Explanation of Cap Rates\n________________________________________\nColin Brechbill - Sunday, March 25, 2012\nLast week one of our clients told me that he would like to raise some cash to pay his impending federal tax bill. He owns quite a few properties - most are income producing, some land, some warehouses, some offices - and all very marketable. This gentleman is a very logical seller (and logical buyer, for that matter). He knows what motivates him so he knows what motivates buyers. He keeps detailed records, copies of invoices, leases, and tax records, etc. When he tells me the net operating ..\n\nComments (1) | Trackbacks (0) | Permalink \n  \nWarren Buffett speaks on why he would buy Single Family Homes\n________________________________________\nColin Brechbill - Tuesday, March 06, 2012\nListen to Warren Buffett, one of the worlds wealthiest business men talk about his thoughts on buying single family homes. ..\n\nComments (0) | Trackbacks (0) | Permalink \n  \nHow to Evaluate a Real Estate Investment Opportunity\n________________________________________\nColin Brechbill - Wednesday, November 16, 2011\nProperly evaluating a real estate investment opportunity can sometimes be a tricky endeavor. There are many factors that can come into play, and it can be hard to focus in on the things that really matter. While I don’t propose to have a magical formula for finding great real estate investments, I do have over 15 years of experience investing in real estate, and have bought and sold hundreds of homes. Along the way, I’ve learned a thing or two about what makes a good investment,  ..\n\nComments (0) | Trackbacks (0) | Permalink \n  \nForeign Investors Give Boost to Atlanta Real Estate Market\n________________________________________\nColin Brechbill - Monday, September 12, 2011\nForeign Investors Give Boost to Atlanta Real Estate Market: MyFoxATLANTA.com (http://www.myfoxatlanta.com/dpp/news/local_news/Foreign-Investors-Give-Boost-to-Atlanta-Real-Estate-20110912-pm-pk) ATLANTA - The hard-pressed Atlanta real estate market is getting a boost from foreign investors. Strong foreign currencies are helping generate enthusiasm for Atlanta and other U.S. real estate markets. Local companies are offering tours capitalize on that inter ..\n\n\n");
